  <body>
    <segment id="1" parent="14" relname="span">Rent increases upon re-letting aren&apos;t bad as such,</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="1" relname="condition"> if it&apos;s only a small amount,</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="13" relname="span"> they’re very bad however,</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="3" relname="condition"> if the rent suddenly climbs by €100 or €200.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="15" relname="interpretation"> With those kinds of amounts you think twice about whether you really want to stay in the flat.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="7" relname="condition"> If there must be rent increases,</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="16" relname="span"> there should also be a cap to avoid nasty surprises.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="20" relname="span"> This helps the landlords,</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="8" relname="reason"> as they can adjust their expenses through the increase,</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="19" relname="span"> and also the tenants,</segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="10" relname="reason"> as they can plan for a maximum rent increase.</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="17" relname="span"> That the landlords are then slightly restricted in the administration of their property is not a problem,</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="11" relname="reason"> as they have more pull in the end anyway.</segment>
